The paper presents a technique for automatically extracting mutual exclusion invariants from temporal planning instances, which involves identifying invariant templates and formulating invariance conditions that account for the entire structure of the actions and the possible concurrent interactions between them. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-categories, as it deals with automated reasoning and synthesis of invariants in planning domains. Additionally, the paper may also be relevant to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category, as it involves formal reasoning about temporal properties of actions. The paper's focus on identifying a broader set of invariants that result in the generation of fewer multi-valued state variables with larger domains suggests that it may also be relevant to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category, as it involves optimization of data structures used in planning. Finally, the paper's emphasis on the performance of temporal planners suggests that it may also be relevant to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category, as it involves practical considerations for implementing planning systems.
